{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493381"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:08:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1305"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1305"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0,0.01,0.09,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112865"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1305"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1305"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"735"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7590"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7626"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112865"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old cricketer is brought to the emergency department after injuring his left shoulder when he fell over, trying to catch a ball. He complains of pain around his left shoulder and cannot move his arm freely. He feels numbness and tingling in his arm. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the outer aspect of shoulder appears flattened (Image). There is tenderness around his shoulder and mild swelling in deltopectoral groove with obliteration of axillary fold and a prominent acromion process. He resists abduction and external rotation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior dislocation of the shoulder","Bicep tendonitis","Fracture of scapula","Acromioclavicular joint injury","Fracture of clavicle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of the patient, together with the clinical appearance, suggests an \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior dislocation of the shoulder. \u003C/strong\u003EIt is by far the commonest type of dislocation and usually results from forced abduction, external rotation and extension. The arm is usually held in an abducted and externally rotated position after injury. There is\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eloss of the normal contour of the deltoid and the\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eacromion is\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eprominent posteriorly and laterally\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E The humeral head itself may well be palpable anteriorly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBicep tendonitis,\u003C/strong\u003E inflammation of bicep tendon, usually results from overuse of a tendon in a repetitive motion, poor posture, lifting heavy weights or poor technique while playing sports. Patient presents with pain that radiates down the front of the arm or from the shoulder to the neck, weakness around the shoulder joint and a clicking, sound is produced with shoulder movement. In tendonitis flexion of the elbow against resistance aggravates the patient\u0027s pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScapula fractures\u003C/strong\u003E typically result from high-energy trauma. The physical examination reveals swelling, tenderness, crepitus, and ecchymosis over the scapular region.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter a \u003Cstrong\u003Eclavicular fracture, \u003C/strong\u003Ethe patient may cradle the injured extremity with the uninjured arm. The shoulder appears shortened relative to the opposite side. Swelling, ecchymosis, tenderness over the clavicle and a visible deformity may also be seen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter an \u003Cstrong\u003Eacromioclavicular joint injury, \u003C/strong\u003Ethe patient complains of pain over the superior part of the shoulder and restricted shoulder motion. A prominent clavicle with loss of the normal contour of the shoulder is usually seen.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In anterior dislocation of shoulder, the arm is usually held in an abducted and externally rotated position after injury."],"references":["Robinson C \u0026 Aderinto J. Shoulder Dislocations and Fracture-Dislocations. J Bone Joint Surg Am. 2005;87(3):639-50."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94902"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1305"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19596"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19596"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/56303a34-a1b2-4e87-b989-a68a6cc03ff6.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/56303a34-a1b2-4e87-b989-a68a6cc03ff6.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94902"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-07T10:24:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-07T10:24:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1305"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112865"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading"